cells","Neutrophils","Lymphocytes","Eosinophils"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeutrophils\u003C/strong\u003E are the most abundant inflammatory cells in the airways of patients with COPD. They release proteases that contribute to alveolar destruction and stimulate mucus hypersecretion. \u003Cstrong\u003ELymphocytes\u003C/strong\u003E, particularly CD8+ T cells, are also present but in lower numbers. While \u003Cstrong\u003Eeosinophils\u003C/strong\u003E are characteristic of asthma, they are not typically prominent in COPD. \u003Cstrong\u003EBasophils\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Emast cells\u003C/strong\u003E play minor roles in COPD pathogenesis.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThe neutrophilic inflammation in COPD is triggered by various factors including cigarette smoke, bacterial products, and chemokines. These cells contribute to tissue destruction through the release of neutrophil elastase, matrix metalloproteinases, and reactive oxygen species.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Neutrophils are the predominant inflammatory cells in chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD).","Neutrophils contribute to tissue destruction in COPD through release of proteases and reactive oxygen species."],"references":["Kim V, Criner GJ. Chronic bronchitis and chronic obstructive pulmonary disease. Am J Respir Crit Care Med. 2013 Feb 1;187(3):228-37. doi: 10.1164/rccm.201210-1843CI. Epub 2012 Nov 29. PMID: 23204254; PMCID: PMC4951627","Agarwal AK, Raja A, Brown BD. Chronic Obstructive Pulmonary Disease. 2023 Aug 7. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32644707","Mason, R. J., Broaddus, V. C., Martin, T. R., King, T. E., Schraufnagel, D., Murray, J. F., \u0026 Nadel, J. A. (2010). Murray and Nadel\u0027s textbook of respiratory medicine E-book: 2-volume set. Elsevier Health Sciences","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"46989"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15479"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"46989","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/46989"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-15T18:30:42+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-15T18:31:33+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8170"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61536"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4927","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4927"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:14:59+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T09:50:22+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":